docs.abstract: Suburban headquarters are being redesigned to add more amenities that will integrate better with their communities and attract the skilled workers.
docs.snippet: Suburban headquarters are being redesigned to add more amenities that will integrate better with their communities and attract the skilled workers.
docs.lead_paragraph: TYSONS, Va. — After World War II, corporations moved to exclusive gated suburban campuses to escape traffic, crowds and big-city clamor. Now companies are designing a little city hubbub back into suburban headquarters by adding shops, restaurants, hotels, residences and public parks.

headline.main: After Urban Flight, Corporate Campuses Add a Taste of the City

docs.abstract: The malware was revealed as Russian troops remained massed at the Ukrainian border, and after Ukrainian government agencies had their websites defaced.
docs.snippet: The malware was revealed as Russian troops remained massed at the Ukrainian border, and after Ukrainian government agencies had their websites defaced.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Microsoft warned on Saturday evening that it had detected a highly destructive form of malware in dozens of government and private computer networks in Ukraine that appeared to be waiting to be triggered by an unknown actor.

headline.main: Microsoft Warns of Destructive Cyberattack on Ukrainian Computer Networks
headline.print_headline: Microsoft Warns Ukraine Of Malware on Networks

docs.abstract: The FTC Chair’s exclusive conversation with Kara Swisher and Andrew Ross Sorkin.
docs.snippet: The FTC Chair’s exclusive conversation with Kara Swisher and Andrew Ross Sorkin.
docs.lead_paragraph: Yesterday, the Federal Trade Commission and the Department of Justice announced they would work to rewrite merger rules in an approach that would clamp down on big tech deals that have allowed companies like Amazon, Google and Facebook to expand their tentacles across industries and across more areas of our lives. Today, Lina Khan sat down with Kara Swisher and DealBook’s editor Andrew Ross Sorkin in an exclusive interview for The New York Times and CNBC.

headline.main: Exclusive: Lina Khan Is (Still) Bursting Big Tech’s Bubble

docs.abstract: The blockbuster deal for the video game maker came together quickly and opportunistically.
docs.snippet: The blockbuster deal for the video game maker came together quickly and opportunistically.
docs.lead_paragraph: Microsoft’s $68.7 billion deal to buy Activision Blizzard is a blockbuster bid to transform the tech giant’s present and its future. If completed, it would be Microsoft’s largest-ever deal and the biggest all-cash acquisition in history. For such a momentous deal, it came together relatively quickly, we can report.

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Jason Karaian, Sarah Kessler, Stephen Gandel, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

docs.abstract: Activision has a lot of popular games that fit into Microsoft’s plans to build a vast library of titles that can be played on all sorts of devices. The metaverse can wait.
docs.snippet: Activision has a lot of popular games that fit into Microsoft’s plans to build a vast library of titles that can be played on all sorts of devices. The metaverse can wait.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — It is inevitable now that when a big tech company makes a significant, strategic decision — like Microsoft’s plan to spend $70 billion on the video game giant Activision Blizzard — it invokes the metaverse.

headline.main: It’s Not Complicated. Microsoft Wants Activision for Its Games.
headline.print_headline: Microsoft Eyes Activision In Quest to Rule Gaming

docs.abstract: Video games have become weapons that tech titans wield to try to shape our future.
docs.snippet: Video games have become weapons that tech titans wield to try to shape our future.
docs.lead_paragraph: This article is part of the On Tech newsletter. Here is a collection of past columns.

headline.main: With Activision, Microsoft Bets on the Future

docs.abstract: U.S. antitrust leaders said they would focus on the tech industry’s free services as they strengthened the review process for corporate consolidation.
docs.snippet: U.S. antitrust leaders said they would focus on the tech industry’s free services as they strengthened the review process for corporate consolidation.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Top federal antitrust officials on Tuesday announced a review of how they approve mergers and acquisitions, in a broad effort to strengthen enforcement and clamp down on a surge of corporate consolidation, particularly in high tech.

headline.main: Regulators aim to rewrite rules for big mergers.
headline.print_headline: Regulators to Rewrite Rules for Big Mergers

docs.abstract: Cloud computing is slowly changing how Wall Street banks handle their business, but concerns with security remain.
docs.snippet: Cloud computing is slowly changing how Wall Street banks handle their business, but concerns with security remain.
docs.lead_paragraph: Michael W. Lucas made big plans to take a trip around the world in March 2020. He arranged to travel from his home in Detroit to Tokyo, then attend conferences in Hong Kong and Bangalore, India, before making a final stop in Paris.

headline.main: Banks Tiptoe Toward Their Cloud-Based Future
headline.print_headline: Banks Slowly Embrace Their Cloud-Based Future

docs.abstract: Some players, unhappy with Activision in recent years, said the Microsoft deal could reverse a decline in quality.
docs.snippet: Some players, unhappy with Activision in recent years, said the Microsoft deal could reverse a decline in quality.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Drew Bienusa began playing Call of Duty, a first-person shooter game published by Activision Blizzard, he was immediately smitten. He loved how immersive having a digital avatar was, and the game was a favorite among his friends.

headline.main: ‘New Eyes’: Gamers Greet Microsoft’s Activision Deal With Guarded Optimism
headline.print_headline: New Owner  Is Welcomed  By Gamers

byline.original: By Erin Woo and Kellen Browning

docs.abstract: Shareholders called for action after evidence emerged that Bill Gates had sought romantic relationships with employees.
docs.snippet: Shareholders called for action after evidence emerged that Bill Gates had sought romantic relationships with employees.
docs.lead_paragraph: Microsoft has selected a law firm to review its sexual harassment and gender discrimination policies, the company’s board announced on Thursday, after shareholders raised alarms about how Microsoft and Bill Gates, one of its founders, had treated employees, especially women.

headline.main: Microsoft opens a review of its sexual harassment policies.
